==Corporate governance==
[[Kent Kresa]] was the [[CEO]] of the company until he was required to retire in 2003 due to age restrictions. At this point, [[Ronald Sugar]], formerly the [[chief operating officer]], took over as CEO.<ref>{{cite news | first=Seth | last=Lubove | url=http://www.forbes.com/free_forbes/2003/0106/102.html | title=We See You, Saddam | publisher=[[Forbes Magazine]] | date=2003-01-06 | accessdate=2006-04-04 }}</ref>  Sugar also served as the company [[chairman]] of the board.  In January, 2010 Wes Bush succeeded Sugar as CEO and also assumed the position of company president.<ref>http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=awNvIV4IfBdk</ref>

===Corporate headquarters===
Northrop Grumman is headquartered in the [[Century City, Los Angeles, California|Century City]] area of [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>Hyland, Alexa. "[http://www.labusinessjournal.com/article.asp?aID=07175868.47501302.1869270.3457087.7229868.368&aID2=143781 SoCal<U+2019>s Aerospace Sector Still Has Lots of Lift]." ''[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]''. January 11, 2010<!--Date indicated on the page-->. Retrieved on January 10, 2010.</ref><ref>"[http://www.northropgrumman.com/locations/index.html Company Locations]." ''Northrop Grumman''. Retrieved on May 12, 2009.</ref> but on January 4, 2010 announced plans to move to the [[Washington Metropolitan Area]] by 2011.<ref>"[http://voices.washingtonpost.com/economy-watch/2010/01/northrop_grumman_moving_hq_to.html?wpisrc=newsletter The Ticker]." ''Washington Post'', January 4, 2010. Retrieved on January 4, 2010.</ref>

In January 2010 Northrop Grumman announced that it will move its headquarters to the [[Washington, DC area]] so the company can be closer to government customers.<ref name="CroweMove">Crowe, Deborah. "[http://www.labusinessjournal.com/article.asp?aID=143693 Northrop to Move Corporate Office to D.C.]." ''[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]''. January 4, 2010. Retrieved on January 10, 2010.</ref> Wesley Bush, the new CEO of Northrop Grumman, stated that the company needed to be located close to [[Capitol Hill]] lawmakers and officials from intelligence and military communities.<ref name="ProctorFlew">Proctor, Charles. "[http://www.labusinessjournal.com/article.asp?aID=79313354.6576349.1869257.6146618.5233052.895&aID2=143780 Northrop Flew Under the Radar]." ''[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]''. January 11, 2010.<!--Jan 11 is the posted date--> Retrieved on January 10, 2010.</ref> Northrop Grumman considered sites in [[Washington, DC]] and in suburbs in [[Maryland]] and [[Virginia]].<ref name="CroweMove"/> During the time of the announcement the company had not yet selected a headquarters site; the company planned to be at the new headquarters by the northern hemisphere Summer of 2011. Charles Proctor of the ''[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]'' said "In a way, the announcement was not a surprise" due to the trend of aerospace companies moving to the DC area and the fact that the newly hired CEO is from West Virginia. Proctor added that CEOs often move corporate headquarters to places that they want the headquarters located. Larry Kosmont, a Los Angeles area economic development consultant, described the move announcement as a "structural failure at all levels for Los Angeles County."<ref name="ProctorFlew"/>

V. Dion Haynes of the ''[[Washington Post]]'' said that District of Columbia economic development officials were "pitching the city's urban hipness and proximity to Capitol Hill power brokers" to Northrop Grumman. In addition Maryland promoted its highly educated workforce and its large number of federal facilities, while Virginia marketed itself as a state with relatively low taxes.<ref>Haynes, V. Dion. "[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/10/AR2010011002250.html D.C. area jurisdictions vie to become new home of Northrop Grumman headquarters]." ''[[Washington Post]]''. Monday January 11, 2010. Retrieved on February 13, 2010.</ref>

